{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510371"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11528"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11528"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.17,0.62,0.06,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4158"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4158"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37273"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"2110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3376"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman is in a Barrett\u0027s oesophagus surveillance program. She is known to have a 6 cm segment of columnar epithelium confirmed on biopsy to show low grade dysplasia. She has a medical history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her medications include esomeprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer most recent endoscopy confirms the presence of the columnar-lined epithelium and on this occasion two of the biopsies in this region show the presence of adenocarcinoma limited to the muscularis mucosa. There is no evidence of lymph node involvement on endoscopic ultrasound and a CT scan is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["External beam radiotherapy","Radiofrequency ablation","Endoscopic mucosal resection","Neo-adjuvant chemotherapy","Oesophagectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus is a pre-cancerous condition characterised by the histological change (i.e. metaplasia) from simple squamous to columnar epithelium. Progression involves first low-grade dysplasia (LGD) followed by high-grade dysplasia (HGD) and finally intramucosal cancer (IMC). The finding of adenocarcinoma confined to the muscularis mucosa categorises this patient\u0027s disease as IMC or early oesophageal cancer. Given the absence of lymph node involvement or metastases, this lesion receives a TNM classification of T1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndoscopic resection is the basis of treatment for localised, superficial oesophageal adenocarcinoma. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic mucosal resection\u003C/strong\u003E (EMR) would be appropriate. EMR allows for histological assessment, providing further information for more precise staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for the treatment of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus. It may be used following endoscopic mucosal resection to achieve complete eradication of dysplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough once the gold standard treatment for high-grade dysplasia, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophagectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would now be considered inappropriate. Less invasive and highly effective approaches are now widely available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeo-adjuvant chemotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Emay be used in more advanced tumours in order to reduce tumour burden and thus facilitate surgical resection. It would not be required when then malignancy is limited to the mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal beam radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E has a limited role in the treatment of oesophageal cancer. It is typically used in the palliative setting in patients who cannot tolerate additional chemotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with Barrett\u0027s oesophagus require regular endoscopic surveillance to detect dysplasia and oesophageal adenocarcinoma","Early oesophageal adenocarcinomas may be managed with endoscopic therapies"],"references":["Shaheen NJ, Falk GW, Iyer PG, et al. Diagnosis and Management of Barrett\u2019s Esophagus: An Updated ACG Guideline. Am J Gastroenterol 2022; 117:559\u201387.","Barret M, Prat F. Diagnosis and treatment of superficial esophageal cancer. Ann Gastroenterol. 2018;31(3):256-265. doi:10.20524/aog.2018.0252"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37273"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11528"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37273"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-30T18:17:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-30T18:18:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4158"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{